1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 { The Slav defence. This has a reputation for being very solid but white keeps a small space advantage nevertheless. } ( 2... e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 { This is the semi-slav defence. We'll be covering the directions with 2...c6 move order. } ) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 { Against the Slav, I recommend 4.e3, the slow system. We prevent the threat of dxc4. Although this is not the sharpest of the lines, this remains testing. White has a strategic advantage due to the extra space in the centre. } ( 4. Nc3 { This is the Semi-Slav Defence. Black can reach this position from various move orders, so it makes sense to study it individually. Here, I recommend going for the Meran system with } 4... e6 5. e3 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] keeping a space advantage, just like in the Slav-system. Black has plenty of possibilities here. Let me take you through the directions in all of them. } 5... Nbd7 { the main system. } ( { Is a very solid option, and was quite the hot topic a few years ago. Here, I recommend going for the strategically ambitious } 5... a6 6. b3 { [%cal Gb3c4] defending c4 against the threat of dxc4. The critical line here is } 6... Bb4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O { and here black has two options } 9... Bd6 ( 9... Qe7 { was tried by Magnus, but I recommend going for the unknown } 10. h3 $5 { a prophylactic approach against e5. Black has to face some uncomfortable problems. } ) 10. Re1 $5 { looking to push e4 at the right time, and also creating space for the king, which becomes relevant in few variations. The main move here is } 10... h6 { where I recommend going for } 11. Rc1 $5 { with a safe practical edge. } ) ( 5... b6 { a new engine of playing these positions. } 6. Bd3 { we develop normally for the next few moves. } 6... Bb7 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. O-O Be7 9. Rd1 { the critical test. We are keeping an eye against the threat of c5. } 9... Qc7 10. b3 O-O { all this has been tested earlier, but now I recommend going for } 11. a4 $14 { with good practical chances. } ) 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 { I find this to a bit better against the 8...e5 lines. } 7... O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 ( 9... a6 { is a big main line, but here I recommend for a very fresh way of playing with } 10. Ng5 $5 { [%cal Ge3e4] intending Ne4/e4, with a complex position. } ) 10. Be2 Bb7 { the big main line. } ( 10... a6 { is met with } 11. Ng5 $5 { a very sharp and testing way to play. } ) 11. e4 { this is also quite popular. The critical deviations comes after } 11... e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nd4 Neg4 { and now the very rare } 14. Nf5 { With a huge initiative coming up next. There are only 15 games here, but white scores a whopping 75%. The game that caught my attention was } 14... Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 Bb8 ( 15... Bc7 16. Bg5 $16 { Gives us a huge edge. } ) 16. Bg5 Qc7 17. f4 $18 { Where white butchered my friend in (32) Pultinevicius,P (2539) -Gong,Q (2275) 1-0 Chennai 2022 } ) 4... Bf5 { the main line. Nevertheless, black has several decent options. } ( 4... Bg4 { is one of the old main lines. This is supposed to be quite solid. } 5. Qb3 Qb6 { and here I recommend the very unknown but quite testing } 6. Nh4 { stopping Bxf3, and preparing h3. We want to meet the natural } 6... e6 { with } 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bg2 { where white keeps good practical chances to extra space, and the pair of bishops. } ) ( 4... g6 { used to be quite popular, but white keeps a small edge in several ways. I recommend going for the simple and strong } 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Bg4 { this was the big main line. However, white keeps a risk-free edge after } ( 7... a6 { the modern main. Here, I recommend } 8. a4 a5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. b3 $14 { [%cal Gc1a3,Gf3e5,Gc3b5] with a safe and solid edge. } ) 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 b6 10. h3 $14 ) ( 4... a6 { is one of the two lines where we take advantage of the fact that we haven't committed our knight. We go for } 5. Nbd2 $5 Bf5 6. Nh4 Be4 7. Qb3 { with a risk-free edge. } ) ( 4... e6 { we can transpose to Meran with 5.Nc3, but I also cover } 5. Nbd2 { [%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gf1d3] which gives a slightly better version of the Meran. } ) 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 $5 { looking to win the pair of bishops. Black has two main moves here. } 6... Be4 ( 6... Bg6 { is the other main line. Since Black doesn't provoke f3, we go for plans with Qb3. } 7. Bd2 Be7 8. Qb3 $5 Qc7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 { and I recommend going for } 10. cxd5 exd5 11. h4 $5 g5 { trying to win a pawn, we can exploit that with } 12. h5 Rxh5 13. Rxh5 Nxh5 14. e4 $1 { [%csl Gd2,Gf1] opening up the centre. We keep a small advantage. } ) ( 6... Bg4 7. Qb3 { gives white a better version of 4...Bg4 } ) 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 { here, we go for plans with Qc2. } 8... Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O a6 { I found this strong } 12. Kb1 $5 { which was a novelty back then. White has great practical chances. Some sample lines } 12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 c5 ( 13... b5 14. Be2 c5 15. d5 $5 { the point. } 15... exd5 ( 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 { is very testing. } ) 16. Bc1 $5 { white keeps an objective edge } ) 14. g4 { This was played against Vidit twice, and he managed to get a big advantage out of the opening, and later convert the game after } 14... cxd4 15. exd4 $16 { in 1-0 (21) Vidit,S (2716) -Shirov,A (2655) Villa Marina, Douglas, Isle of Man 2023: 1-0 (39) Vidit,S (2724) -Nyzhnyk,I (2687) Saint Louis 2022 } *
