1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3] as discussed in the introduction, this move gives white a small strategic edge due to the extra space. } 4... Bf5 { [%cal Ye7e6] black's typical response in the Slav. The bishop comes out of the pawn chain, and therefore black can play e6 without worrying about the prospects of the bishop. However, the drawback is that the bishop may be attacked. } 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 { [%csl Rf5][%cal Yh4f5] the point. We threaten Nxf5, with the very simple strategic goal of winning the pair of bishops. Black has three moves here, but we'll begin with the principled } 6... Be4 { provoking f3 } 7. f3 { we create some weaknesses on the kingside, but also gain control of the crucial e4-square. } ( 7. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 $15 { [%csl Rd4,Ge4,Rh4][%cal Gg7g5,Rc6c5,Gb8c6] } ) 7... Bg6 8. Bd2 $5 { An important intermezzo. We develop our bishop, and our waiting for Black to commit to Be7, so that we can take on g6. This is more flexible than Nxg6. The lines with Be4-Bg6 and direct Bg6 are often confusing so here's the rule of thumb. When black doesn't provoke f3 we go for plans with Qb3. If black provokes f3, we go for plans with Qc2. a very possible alternative is } 8... Nbd7 { the main move of this chapter. Black is delaying committing the bishop. We stay consistent with our plan } ( 8... Be7 { This is black's main response usually, which we cover in depth in this and the following chapter. } 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 { [%cal Ge1c1] the thematic plan } 10... Nbd7 ( 10... a6 { doesn't have an independent value. } 11. O-O-O dxc4 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 Nbd7 { transposes. } ) 11. O-O-O { [%cal Ge3e4] We safeguard our king, and now want to increase space in the centre with e4. This chapter'll cover 11...dxc4 and the other sidelines. The next chapter covers black's main move, 11...a6. } 11... dxc4 { the main move of this chapter. } ( 11... Qc7 { is thematic, but weaker. We can opt for the typical } 12. cxd5 exd5 ( 12... cxd5 { [%csl Rd7] } 13. Kb1 $1 { [%cal Ge3e4] the king is out of the danger zone, so we are ready to push e4 next. } 13... Rc8 ( 13... Rxh2 $4 14. Rxh2 Qxh2 15. Nb5 Kf8 16. Nxa7 $18 ) 14. e4 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge4,Gf1] } ) 13. h4 $1 { our thematic plan, which you'll see in chapter 6 too. } 13... O-O-O ( 13... Nh5 $4 { [%cal Rh5g3] } 14. Nxd5 $18 ) 14. Bd3 Nf8 15. g4 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Gd3,Gg4,Rg6,Gh4][%cal Yd1g1,Yh4h5] } ) ( 11... Nb6 { was tried by Fabi at the candidates, but this takes time. } 12. c5 Nbd7 13. Be1 $14 { [%cal Yd8c7,Ge1g3,Yg2g4] prophylaxis against Qc7. White keeps a healthy advantage. } 13... b6 ( 13... O-O 14. g4 b6 15. Na4 $14 { [%cal Gh2h4, Gh4h5] } ) 14. Na4 bxc5 15. dxc5 $14 { [%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] } ) ( 11... a5 { is met with the typical } 12. cxd5 $14 exd5 ( 12... cxd5 { [%csl Rb5] } 13. Kb1 $16 ) 13. Kb1 $16 { [%cal Yh2h4,Yh4h5,Ge3e4] } ) 12. Bxc4 b5 13. Be2 { [%cal Ge3e4] White has a good strategic edge here, thanks to the extra space and the pair of bishops. Black needs to challenge it or things will become considerably worse. } 13... a6 14. Kb1 $1 { transposes to the next chapter. } ) 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 { [%cal Ge1c1] preparing 0-0-0. Here, Be7 transposes to the main line 8...Be7, but Black has some other options } 10... dxc4 { the key deviation. Black claims to have a better version of the main line since Black hasn't committed the bishop. However, we haven't committed our king to the queenside so we retain some flexibility too. } ( 10... Qc7 { is possible, but we opt for the typical pawn sac here. } 11. cxd5 exd5 ( 11... cxd5 12. O-O-O $14 { [%csl Gd4,Rd7,Ge4][%cal Ge3e4] this structure is usually solid, but with the knight on d7, white has a good position thanks to the pair of bishops and the possible pawn break with e4. } ) 12. O-O-O $1 { we aren't afraid of } 12... Rxh2 { as we have the typical } 13. Rxh2 Qxh2 14. e4 $36 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Re8,Rf7,Rg6][%cal Ye4e5,Ye5e6] with the typical initiative. } 14... Nb6 ( 14... dxe4 15. fxe4 $14 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] } ) 15. e5 Nfd7 16. e6 $1 { the point } 16... Nf6 17. g4 $40 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Ye6f7,Gf1d3] we keep good attacking prospects. } ) 11. Bxc4 b5 ( { is an inferior version for black strategically. Black has given up the centre control for no reason. We keep a solid edge after } 11... Qc7 12. g3 $1 { and after something like } 12... a6 { we have } 13. Ne4 $1 Be7 14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. O-O-O $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd2,Gd4][%cal Ge3e4] with a sound objective edge. } ) 12. Be2 a6 { [%cal Gc6c5] and here, since we haven't committed to 0-0-0, we can target the c6-pawn with } 13. Ne4 $1 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Gc2c6] with an easier game. Some sample lines- } 13... Nxe4 14. fxe4 $1 { [%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge4] keeping a strong centre. } 14... Rc8 ( 14... c5 15. a4 Rc8 { tr. } ) 15. a4 $1 { [%csl Ra6,Rb5,Rc6] attacking weaknesses, trying to include the rook into the game. } 15... c5 16. d5 $1 { important. we keep the c-file closed. White keeps a much easier game. } 16... c4 ( 16... exd5 $6 17. axb5 $14 ) 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. axb5 axb5 19. O-O Bd6 20. e5 $1 { [%csl Rg6] } 20... Nxe5 21. h3 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Ge2, Re8,Gg1] White has a small objective advantage, but a big advantage practically, due to the black king being stuck in the centre. } *
