1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 { seems more testing than Qb3 } 8... Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O a6 { the starting point of the chapter. } 12. Kb1 $1 { This was the novelty I discussed in the introduction. We side-step out of the c-file, and are looking to open up the position with e4. } 12... dxc4 { the critical test. } ( 12... Qc7 { is met with the thematic } 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e4 $14 { [%cal Gc2b3] } ) 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Be2 c5 { striking our centre. Now dxc5 Bxc5 gives black a good game, but we have the very testing } 15. d5 { possible. In this chapter, we'll cover } 15... exd5 { for Black. Black wins a pawn, but we challenge that with } 16. Bc1 $1 { the entire point. We want to play Nxd5 next, where we keep an advantage due to the better development, safer king and pair of bishops. } ( 16. f4 { is met with } 16... b4 $1 { [%cal Gd8a5] } ) 16... Qb6 { the most critical one,which is already tough to find for Black. } ( 16... Nb6 { is the most natural move, but after } 17. g4 $14 { White has a very comfortable game. } 17... b4 18. Na4 c4 19. g5 Nfd7 20. h4 { [%cal Ye3e4,Yh4h5] } 20... Qc7 21. e4 c3 22. Nxb6 Nxb6 23. exd5 $14 ) ( 16... d4 $2 17. exd4 c4 18. g4 Nb6 19. d5 $16 { 1-0 (45) Maghsoodloo,P (2707) -Lagunow,R (2425) Doha 2023 } ) ( 16... Qc7 17. g4 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gg4g5] } 17... Nb6 ( 17... Rxh2 18. Rxh2 Qxh2 19. g5 $18 { [%csl Rd5, Re8][%cal Gc3d5] } ) 18. g5 Nh5 19. f4 $1 { [%cal Ye2f3] keeping full control.The play becomes non-forcing, so you don't need to memorise the following sequence of moves. } 19... O-O-O 20. a4 $1 { [%csl Rb5,Rb6,Rd5][%cal Ga4a5] } 20... d4 21. a5 dxc3 ( 21... Na8 22. exd4 cxd4 23. Qe4 $18 ) 22. axb6 Qxb6 23. Qxc3 { [%cal Ge3e4] } 23... c4 24. Bf3 $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gc3,Rc8,Gf3,Rh5] } ) 17. f4 $1 { [%cal Ge2f3] Only in this line, we go for f4, as b4 is met with Nd5! } 17... Qe6 { The critical reply. } ( 17... Rd8 { is the other critical line. } 18. Bf3 $1 { [%cal Gc3d5,Yf3d5] } ( 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Rxd5 c4 $11 ) 18... O-O 19. g4 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gg4g5,Gc3d5] } ( 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 c4 21. h4 Bc5 $13 ) 19... d4 $1 20. Ne2 { [%cal Gg4g5] } 20... d3 { the critical test. } ( 20... Qe6 21. Rhg1 $14 { [%cal Gf4f5] } ) ( 20... dxe3 $6 21. g5 Nh5 22. Bxe3 $16 { [%cal Gf4f5] } ) 21. Rxd3 c4 { [%cal Ge7c5] } 22. Rd4 $1 { the last move to know in this sequence. } 22... Bc5 ( 22... Nc5 23. g5 Nh5 24. Bd5 Nd3 25. Rxd3 $1 cxd3 26. Qxd3 $14 { [%csl Gd5,Rg8,Rh5][%cal Ye3e4,Ye2g3] } ) 23. h4 $1 Bxd4 24. Nxd4 $14 { [%csl Gd4,Gf3][%cal Rh4h5] } 24... Nc5 25. h5 Nd3 26. h6 $14 { [%cal Gh6g7,Gc2h2] } ) ( 17... c4 18. g4 $16 ) ( 17... O-O 18. Bf3 Rac8 19. g4 d4 20. Ne2 $14 dxe3 ( 20... d3 21. Rxd3 c4 22. Rd4 $16 ) 21. Bxe3 $18 ) ( 17... b4 18. Nxd5 { [%csl Rb6][%cal Gd5b6] } ) 18. Bf3 Nb6 19. e4 { [%csl Re8] opening up the position. Principled, as the king is in the centre. } 19... d4 ( 19... dxe4 20. Rhe1 $14 ) 20. f5 $1 Qe5 ( 20... gxf5 21. exf5 $16 { [%csl Re8] } ) 21. g3 $1 { important! } 21... Nfd7 ( 21... c4 22. Bf4 Qc5 23. e5 Nfd5 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 25. fxg6 ) ( 21... dxc3 22. Bf4 $18 ) 22. Bf4 Qf6 23. g4 $1 { strengthening f5, to prepare e5. } 23... dxc3 ( 23... Ne5 24. g5 Qd6 25. Nd5 $14 ) 24. e5 Nxe5 25. Bxa8 Nxg4 ( 25... Nxa8 26. Qe4 Nc6 ) 26. Rhe1 $1 O-O 27. Bf3 gxf5 28. b3 { [%cal Gh2h3] Although we are down on material, we remain better due to the threat of h3-Be5. } 28... Qh4 ( 28... c4 29. h3 Nh6 30. Be5 $18 ) 29. Re2 g6 30. Bg3 $16 { [%cal Gh2h3] } *
