1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O a6 12. Kb1 $1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Be2 c5 15. d5 Nxd5 { the starting point of this chapter. } 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Bc3 { our point. If we get Rxd5 in comfortably, we should have a good position thanks to the strategic edge. } 17... b4 { the critical defence. Other moves are weaker. } ( 17... Nf6 $2 18. g4 $1 O-O 19. g5 Nh5 20. f4 $18 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Ge2f3,Yf4f5] } ) ( 17... O-O $5 18. Rxd5 $14 ( 18. f4 $5 ) ) 18. Bxg7 $1 Rh7 { [%csl Re8,Rg7] Black's point is revealed. Our bishop cannot be defended. That being said, black still has the king in the centre. } 19. Rxd5 $1 Rxg7 20. Rhd1 { [%csl Rd7] } 20... Ra7 { the only real defence. We are following So-MVL. } 21. Qa4 { [%csl Rd7][%cal Ge2b5] setting up the cheeky Bb5. } 21... Qc8 $1 22. f4 $14 { [%cal Ge2f3] a strong novelty. We threaten Bf3-Bc6. } ( 22. Bb5 { was tried in the aforementioned game. The players agreed to draw after } 22... axb5 23. Qxa7 Nf6 24. Re5 Nd7 $11 ) 22... c4 $1 { [%cal Gc4c3,Yc3c2] only this precise move holds. } ( 22... f5 23. Bf3 Bf8 24. e4 $14 ) 23. Bf3 { [%cal Yd5d7,Rf3c6] } 23... Kd8 $3 { [%csl Rd7,Rd8][%cal Gd1d7] again, the only move for black. This is not easy to play practically, with the rooks aiming directly towards the d-file. } 24. e4 $5 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf3g4,Yf7f5] We keep on improving our position, as there is absolutely risk thanks to the weak black king. } ( { we can always take a perpetual with } 24. Qa5+ Ke8 25. Qa4 $11 ) 24... c3 { again, only this counterattacking move holds. Black is walking along a tight rope. } 25. bxc3 bxc3 26. Kc2 { preventing c2. Black is forced to play } 26... Rb7 $1 { which is not obvious at all. } ( 26... Ke8 { runs into } 27. e5 $18 { [%cal Gd5d7] threatening Rxd7. } ) 27. Be2 { [%cal Ge2a6] since the rook has moved, we can try to target the a6 pawn and improve our bishop. } ( 27. e5 Rb2+ 28. Kc1 Rb7 $1 { [%cal Gc3c2] } 29. Kc2 $11 ) 27... Rb2+ 28. Kc1 { and now black needs to play the very concrete } 28... Ke8 { which is practically impossible. } ( { instead, } 28... Rb7 { runs into } 29. Bxa6 c2 30. Qxc2 Qxc2+ 31. Kxc2 Rc7+ 32. Kb3 $14 { [%cal Ga6b5] where white keeps pressure. } ) 29. Rxd7 Kf8 { It's still not over, as after } 30. Qa5 { black needs to spot } 30... Rb1+ $3 ( 30... Rb8 31. Bxa6 $18 ) 31. Kxb1 c2+ 32. Kb2 cxd1 $1 { and black escapes. } 33. Rxd1 Rh7 $1 34. Qd5 { [%cal Ge2c4] } 34... Rh4 35. Rf1 Rxf4 36. Rxf4 Qb8+ { clearly, not an easy line for Black. } *
