1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Be4 7. f3 Bg6 8. Bd2 { seems more testing than Qb3 } 8... Be7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Qc2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O a6 12. Kb1 $1 dxc4 13. Bxc4 c5 { the starting point of this chapter. Black doesn't spend time on b5 and pushes the bishop back. Instead, he challenges the centre immediately. } 14. g4 $1 { the most testing move. We intend to increase our strategic edge by gaining space with g5-f4. } ( { the comp also like this, but after } 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Be1 Qb8 $1 { I found black to be in great shape. } ) 14... Nb6 { the best move in the position, albeit a difficult one. } ( 14... b5 $2 { is natural, but runs into } 15. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 16. g5 $16 { Black has a horrible pawn structure, so giving up the piece doesn't make sense. If black tries to keep the piece on the board with } 16... Nh5 { we have } 17. Qxg6+ Kf8 18. Ne4 $1 { [%cal Gd4c5] with a decisive attack. } 18... c4 19. Qxe6 $18 ) ( 14... cxd4 $6 { was tried in both the games played by Vidit. However, after } 15. exd4 $16 { he already had a great advantage. } 15... Nb6 16. Bb3 Rc8 17. Qd3 $1 { stopping Nc4. } 17... Nbd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. f4 $1 { [%cal Gf4f5] the last crucial move. You look to open up the position with f5 next. He went on to win both the games with ease. } 19... Qd7 20. f5 gxf5 21. gxf5 exf5 22. Rde1 $16 { 1-0 (20) Vidit,S (2716) -Shirov,A (2655) } 22... Nf6 { 1-0 (39) Vidit,S (2724) -Nyzhnyk,I (2687) Saint Louis 2022 } ) 15. dxc5 $1 { Mishra tried this in both of his games, } 15... Nxc4 16. Qa4+ Nd7 17. Qxc4 Nxc5 18. Ne4 $1 { [%cal Gd2c3] vacating the c3-square for the bishop. } 18... Nxe4 ( 18... b5 19. Qc2 Qd3 20. Qxd3 Nxd3 21. Bc3 $14 { [%csl Rg7][%cal Ge4d6,Yc3g7] gives white a pleasant endgame } ) 19. Qxe4 Qd5 ( 19... Qb6 { was tried by Donchenko. Mishra continued with } 20. Bc3 Bf6 { and here the subtle } 21. Bd4 { poses some practical problems for Black. } 21... Qc6 ( 21... Bxd4 22. exd4 $14 { [%csl Re8][%cal Gd4d5,Yh2h4,Yh4h5] } ) 22. Qxc6+ bxc6 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. h4 $5 { [%csl Ra6,Rc6][%cal Gh4h5,Yd1d4,Yd4c4,Yc4a4,Yd1d2,Yd2h2] } ) 20. Qxd5 exd5 21. h3 Rd8 22. Bc3 f6 23. h4 Kf7 24. Kc2 $14 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gc2d3] White has a significantly easier endgame. } *
