1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bf5 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nh4 Bg6 { the critical move of this chapter. Black doesn't provoke f3. } ( 6... Bg4 { is an inferior version of the 4...Bg4 line. } 7. Qb3 $6 dxc4 { tried by some top players recently, but we have nothing to be worried about. } ( 7... Qc7 { runs into the typical } 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. g5 Nfd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Bd2 Be7 13. f4 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Gd4,Gf1,Gf4][%cal Yh3h4,Yh4h5,Yf1e2] } ) ( 7... Qb6 { We have a very similar structure (Bishop on g4, and knight on h4) to the 4...Bg4 line. We can continue with } 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 { and here, instead of the typical Nxg6-Bg2, we can opt for } 10. c5 $1 { exploiting the fact the c3 knight controls e4. } 10... Qc7 11. g5 Nfd7 12. Bd2 $14 { [%cal Gh4g6,Yf2f4] followed by Nxg6 & f4, keeping a solid edge. } ) 8. Qxb7 Nbd7 9. h3 $1 { an useful inclusion. We keep the option of playing Bh5 g4 open at some point. } 9... Bh5 10. Qxc6 Rc8 11. Qb5 Nd5 { trying to open up the a5-e1 diagonal. } 12. Nxd5 exd5 { Qxd5 runs into Bb4+, and so we start with } 13. Nf3 $16 { with a big edge. If black sticks to the original plan with } 13... Rb8 { we have } 14. Qxd5 Bb4+ 15. Nd2 $18 { with a decisive advantage. } ) 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Bd2 Nbd7 ( 8... Bd6 $6 9. Qb3 Qc7 10. Rc1 { the point is that we now threaten cxd5-Nb5. Note that } 10... Rxh2 { doesn't work. } ( 10... Nbd7 $4 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 $18 ) 11. Rxh2 Bxh2 12. g3 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qxg3+ 14. Kd1 $18 { [%csl Rb7,Re8][%cal Gd1c2,Gc2b1] } ) 9. Qb3 { as pointed out in the introduction, we go for Qb3 plans, if our opponent hasn't provoked f3. } ( 9. Bd3 Bd6 ) 9... Qc7 { the critical test. } ( 9... Qb6 { gives white a risk-free advantage. Some sample lines- } 10. Be2 Be7 ( 10... Qxb3 11. axb3 g5 ( 11... a6 12. f4 $14 { [%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Rg6g5,Yg2g4,Yh2h4] } ) ( 11... Bb4 12. Kd1 { [%cal Gd1c2,Yf2f3,Yg2g4,Yh2h4] } ) 12. f3 { [%cal Ge1f2] And white's position looks slightly more pleasant } ) 11. h3 $5 O-O ( 11... g5 12. O-O-O Qxb3 13. axb3 O-O-O 14. Kc2 ) 12. O-O Qc7 13. Qc2 $14 ) ( 9... Rb8 $14 10. cxd5 exd5 11. f3 $14 { [%cal Ge3e4] } ) 10. cxd5 exd5 ( 10... cxd5 $4 { [%csl Rd7] runs into } 11. Rc1 $18 { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gc3b5] } ) 11. h4 $5 { a novelty in practical play. We want to provoke g5. } 11... g5 { other moves are considerably weaker. } ( 11... Be7 $14 12. Be2 $14 { [%csl Gd2,Ge2,Rg6,Rg7] } 12... b5 ( 12... g5 13. h5 $14 ) 13. Rc1 $14 ) ( 11... Bd6 $14 12. Be2 $14 ) 12. h5 $1 { the point. We want the knight to be deflected to h5, so that we can open up the position with e4. } 12... Rxh5 ( 12... g4 $14 13. O-O-O Rxh5 14. Rxh5 Nxh5 15. e4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 { transposes. } ) 13. Rxh5 Nxh5 14. e4 $1 dxe4 15. Nxe4 { With great practical chances. } 15... g4 $1 { retaining the pawn. } ( { the natural } 15... O-O-O $14 { is weaker. White keeps an edge after } 16. Nxg5 Re8+ 17. Kd1 Nhf6 18. Rc1 $14 ) 16. O-O-O Ndf6 $1 { [%cal Gc7f7] This artificial move holds for black. } ( 16... Nhf6 17. Ng5 Nd5 18. Bd3 $14 ) 17. Nxf6+ $5 Nxf6 18. Re1+ Be7 19. Qe3 Kf8 ( 19... c5 $1 { this accurate move holds for Black. } 20. Qg5 cxd4+ 21. Kb1 Kf8 22. Qh4 Kg8 23. Bg5 { [%cal Gf1d3] it seems like white is putting pressure, but } 23... Qa5 $1 { solves all of Black's problems. Still, this is not easy to play on the board. } 24. Rd1 Ne4 $1 { with a perpetual after } ( 24... Qa4 { allows to maintain the pressure with } 25. b3 Qa5 26. Bd3 Re8 27. Rh1 $44 ) 25. Bxe7 Nd2+ 26. Ka1 Nb3+ 27. Kb1 $11 ) 20. Bc4 Rd8 ( 20... Qd7 21. Rh1 Kg8 22. Qd3 b5 23. Bb3 c5 24. Qg3 $40 ) 21. Rh1 Kg8 22. Qg5 Rxd4 23. Bb3 $40 { White exerts a lot of pressure over the black king. } *
