1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 { the starting point of this chapter. Black deviates from 4...Bf5, the main line. With Bg4, White keeps pressure over the f3-knight. Looks more logical, but the bishop is always subject to attack via h3. } 5. Qb3 { We attack the b7-pawn as usual. } 5... Qb6 { Black's main move in the position. The other alternatives are covered in the next chapter. White usually plays Nc3/Ne5 here, but I propose the very fresh and testing } 6. Nh4 $5 { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3] here. We prevent all Bxf3 ideas, and look to attack the bishop next with h3. } 6... e6 $14 { the most natural and logical way of playing, but this is precisely what we were hoping for. } ( { Black's best bet is to play } 6... Nbd7 $1 { or 6... g6, with the intention of meeting } 7. h3 { with } 7... Be6 $1 { The best way to equalise. Black will develop with g6 next, maintaining pressure on c4. This is not at all easy to play. } ( 7... Bh5 8. Nc3 e6 9. g4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bg2 { transposes. } ) 8. Nc3 g6 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Bd2 O-O { transposes. } ) ( 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 $14 ) ( 6... g6 { starting with this move order also makes sense. } 7. Bd2 Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Be6 10. Nf3 Nbd7 { we transpose back. } 11. cxd5 $1 Qxb3 { the right approach. Black needs to enter the complications } ( 11... Nxd5 12. Ng5 Qxb3 13. axb3 { transposes. } ) ( 11... cxd5 12. Bd3 $14 { [%csl Rd7] } ) 12. axb3 Nxd5 ( 12... Bxd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. b4 { gives white some chances because of the pair of bishops. } 14... e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. O-O-O { [%csl Gd2,Gf1][%cal Gb4b5,Ye3e4]  We keep some chances due to the bishop pair. Our plans revolve around eliminating the b-pawn, or gaining space in the centre. } ) 13. Ng5 { We intend to win the bishop with Ne6, so black needs to enter the following forcing line } 13... Nb4 $1 14. Nxe6 Nc2+ 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Nxf8 Kxf8 17. Bc4 { [%csl Ra1][%cal Gd1e2] } 17... b5 18. Ke2 bxc4 19. Rxa1 cxb3 { we are a pawn down, but after } 20. Ra5 { [%csl Ra7,Rb3,Rc6][%cal Gc3e4] intending Ne4/f4, we keep some pressure. Black can try to eliminate our central pawn with } 20... e5 { but we still retain pressure with } 21. d5 cxd5 22. Rxd5 Ke7 23. e4 $5 { [%csl Ra7,Rb3][%cal Gd2e3,Yc3a4,Yd2b4,Rd5b5] } ) 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 { [%csl Rh5] } 8... Bg6 ( 8... Qxb3 9. axb3 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bg2 { transposes. } ) ( 8... g5 $14 { looks interesting, but after } 9. gxh5 gxh4 10. Qc2 $14 { we keep a healthy edge. } 10... Nxh5 $2 11. Nc3 { we intend to finish our development and follow up by opening the centre. } 11... Nd7 12. Bd2 Be7 13. O-O-O Nhf6 14. cxd5 exd5 ( 14... cxd5 15. Kb1 $16 { [%csl Re8] } ) 15. e4 $16 ) 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. Bg2 $14 { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Gd4,Gg2] White has a stable edge due to the pair of bishops and the centre. } 10... Qxb3 ( 10... Nbd7 11. Nc3 g5 $1 { [%csl Rh3] fixing our pawn. } ( 11... Be7 $6 { allows us to further expand our position with } 12. g5 Nh5 13. h4 $16 { [%cal Gc1d2,Gf2f4] } ) ( 11... Qa6 { has been tried by some elite players, but is comfortably met with } 12. cxd5 Nxd5 ( 12... exd5 $6 13. g5 Nh5 14. e4 $16 { [%csl Gd4,Ge4,Re8] } ) 13. Bd2 $14 { where we keep a stable edge. Note that } 13... Nb4 { runs into } 14. Bf1 $18 { [%csl Rb4] where black has troubles with the b4-knight. } ) 12. cxd5 { we release the tension at the right time. } 12... Qxb3 ( 12... exd5 13. Qc2 $14 { [%csl Rg5][%cal Ge1g1,Ge3e4] looking to exploit the g5-pawn. } ) ( 12... Nxd5 { has been tried in few games, but after } 13. Qc2 Nb4 14. Qe2 $14 { [%cal Ge1g1,Gc1d2] we keep a safe and sound edge. } ) 13. axb3 { [%csl Ra7,Rb3][%cal Ga1a7] The pawn is weak, but our rook is activated. } 13... Nxd5 $1 ( 13... exd5 $6 { is met with the typical } 14. e4 { [%csl Rg5] exploiting the weak g5-pawn } 14... Nxe4 ( 14... dxe4 15. Bxg5 $14 ) 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Bxg5 Bb4 17. Ke2 Bxc3 ( 17... O-O 18. Nxe4 $14 ) 18. bxc3 $16 ) 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. e4 { [%csl Rg5] going for the thematic break } 15... dxe4 16. Bxg5 Be7 17. Bxe7 Kxe7 18. Bxe4 Nf6 19. Bf3 Rhd8 20. O-O-O $14 { Black has some compensation, but we keep better chances due to the extra pawn and the presence of the light-squared bishop. } ) 11. axb3 g5 { [%csl Rh3] } ( 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 Bb4 13. Bd2 { [%cal Gg4g5,Ye1e2,Yh1c1] We have the typical advantage. } 13... a5 $6 { looking to castle long, but this creates some weaknesses. } ( 13... O-O 14. Ke2 $16 { [%cal Gf2f4,Yg4g5,Yh3h4,Yh4h5] } ) 14. Ke2 O-O-O 15. Rhc1 $16 { [%csl Ra5][%cal Gc3b1] } ) 12. Nc3 { [%csl Rg5][%cal Ge3e4,Gc1g5] we are all set to push e4 next. } 12... Be7 ( 12... Bb4 { stops e4, but is met with the thematic } 13. Bd2 $14 { [%cal Ge1e2,Gc3a2,Ga2c1,Gc1d3] followed by Ke2, and rerouting of knight to d3. } ) ( 12... Na6 13. Bd2 Nb4 14. Ke2 $14 { [%cal Ga1a4,Gc4c5] } ) 13. e4 $5 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] } 15... Nd7 16. Kf1 a6 17. Kg2 O-O-O 18. Rd1 $14 { [%cal Yd4d5] We want to open up the position with d5 next. White has a much easier game and is a safe two-result position. } *
