native. } ) 6... Be4 { the critical try. } ( 6... Bxg2 $4 { has been played in most of the games, but after } 7. Bxg2 Nbd7 8. Nc3 $18 { [%csl Gb7,Gc1, Gc3,Gc4,Rc6,Gg2] white keeps a decisive advantage thanks to the activity. } ) ( 6... Nbd7 7. gxf3 $16 { white keeps an advantage thanks to the extra material. } ) 7. Qxa8 Qc7 { [%csl Ra8] black is hoping to trap our queen. } 8. Bd2 $16 { [%cal Gb1c3,Ga1c1] preparing a quick Nc3-Rc1 and cxd5. } 8... e6 9. Nc3 Be7 { black prepares 0-0 & Nbd7. } ( 9... dxc4 $6 { is an inferior version of the text. } 10. Bxc4 Be7 11. f3 Bg6 $4 12. Nb5 $18 ) 10. f3 { looking to deflect the bishop from the defence of the d5-pawn. } 10... O-O $1 ( 10... Bg6 $4 { runs into } 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 $1 { the point of the operation. } 12... cxb5 13. Rc1 Qd8 14. Bxb5+ Kf8 15. Qxa7 $18 { [%csl Gb5,Rb8,Gd2,Rd8,Rf8][%cal Yd2a5] black is busted due to the weak king and active white pieces. } ) 11. fxe4 Nbd7 { black wins the queen, but after } 12. Qxf8+ Nxf8 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. e5 $14 { White keeps a stable edge thanks to the enormous material advantage. White has two rooks and a pawn for the queen. } *
