1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Nbd2 $5 { [%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gf1d3,Ge1g1] Generally, this is a more flexible move in these structures. With the knight on c3, Black usually is looking to play Bd6-e5. However, with the knight on d2, we can go for the b3-Bb2 setup, where the e5 square is very well-defended. Based on what Black does, our intended setup is b3-Bb2-Bd3-0-0, followed by e4 or Ne5, or some attack on the queenside.In this chapter, we'll be covering black's most played setup, Nbd7-Bd6-b6. } ( 5. Nc3 $5 { transposes to Meran } ) 5... Nbd7 ( { another possible move order is to start with } 5... Bd6 6. b3 O-O 7. Bd3 { since black hasn't played Nd7 (intending e5) , we start with Bd3 to keep the option of early e4 } 7... b6 ( 7... Nbd7 8. Bb2 { transposes. } ) 8. O-O Bb7 9. e4 $1 { the right time to open up the centre. } ( 9. Bb2 { runs into } 9... c5 { where black is doing quite alright. } ) 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] We enjoy a healthy advantage thanks to the extra space in the centre. Therefore, strategically speaking, black needs to challenge our centre with } 11... f5 $1 ( { other moves like } 11... Nd7 { are weaker. After } 12. Re1 Nf6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxf6 $14 { [%csl Rb7,Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] we keep a stable positional advantage. } ) 12. Bd3 c5 { the point. Black challenges our d4 pawn and activates the b7-bishop. However, this weakens the e6-pawn which we try to exploit with } 13. Re1 $1 Qf6 ( 13... Nc6 $6 14. d5 exd5 15. cxd5 $16 { [%csl Gd3,Gd5,Re6][%cal Yd3c4] } ) 14. Bg5 $1 Qg6 15. Qe2 $5 { [%csl Re6] } 15... Re8 16. d5 $1 { [%csl Re6] constantly hammering the weakness. } 16... Na6 { the only move to maintain equality. } ( { the natural } 16... Nd7 $2 { runs into } 17. Qxe6+ $3 Rxe6 18. Rxe6 Qf7 19. Rxd6 $18 { [%csl Rb7,Gd3,Gd5,Gd6,Rd7,Re6,Rf7,Gg5][%cal Ga1e1,Yd6e6,Re6e7] where keeps a decisive advantage. } ) ( 16... e5 { runs into } 17. g4 $1 e4 ( 17... Bc8 18. Qe3 $16 { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] } ) 18. gxf5 $16 ) 17. Qxe6+ $5 Rxe6 18. Rxe6 Qxe6 $1 ( 18... Qf7 19. Rxd6 $18 ) 19. dxe6 Bxf3 20. gxf3 h6 21. Be3 g6 $1 22. Bxh6 Nc7 $11 { we keep some pressure, but black is fine objectively. However, the line is clearly not easy to play for Black. Finding Na6 and then Qxe6 is very inhuman. } ) 6. b3 { we stick to our setup } 6... Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O { the best move order for black. Black keeps more flexibility, and may opt for another setup apart from the most trusted b6. } ( 7... b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 { is met with the thematic } 9. e4 $1 ( 9. O-O { unfortunately is fine for black after } 9... O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 { and now the thematic } 12... Nf6 $11 { [%cal Yc6c5] followed by c5. } ) 9... dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 { In these structures, we are not really bothered about Bb4+ } 11... Bb4+ ( 11... Nf6 { isn't threatening either. We can stick true to our plan and play } 12. Bc2 c5 ( 12... Bb4+ 13. Kf1 { transposes. } ) 13. Qe2 $1 { [%cal Ge1c1] } 13... cxd4 14. O-O-O $1 { with good attacking prospects. } 14... Qe7 15. Nxd4 O-O ( 15... Ba3 16. Nb5 Bxb2+ 17. Kxb2 $14 ) ( 15... O-O-O 16. Kb1 $14 ) 16. Rhe1 Ba3 17. g4 $16 ) 12. Kf1 $1 { [%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] the point. White's king is very safe, and we will include the rook in the game via h4. } 12... Nf6 ( 12... Bd6 13. Ne5 $14 ) 13. Bc2 Bd6 14. h4 $1 c5 15. h5 h6 16. Qe2 { [%cal Yd4d5] forcing black to castle } 16... O-O 17. Rh3 { we bring out our rook into the action } 17... Qc7 ( 17... cxd4 18. Nxd4 $14 ) 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Ne5 $16 { [%cal Gh3e3,Rh3g3] White stands better due to the attacking prospects on the kingside. } ) ( 7... Qe7 { [%cal Re6e5] black wants to play e5 next, and so we stop in the typical fashion with } 8. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Gf1d3] } ( 8. Bd3 $6 e5 $11 ) 8... Ba3 { the most played move. However, we are happy to trade our bad bishop with } 9. Bxa3 Qxa3 10. Qc2 $14 { [%cal Gf2f4,Yf1e2,Gf1d3,Ye1g1] where we keep an edge. All we need to develop pieces and play f4. } ) 8. Bd3 b6 { the main choice of black players. Black wants to 