1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 { [%cal Yb7b5,Yc8f5] a flexible move. Black wants to push b5 at some point, gaining space on the queenside. The other idea is to play Bf5, and to meet Qb3 with b5. } 5. Nbd2 { we continue developing normally. } 5... Bf5 { the preferred choice of most black players. } 6. Nh4 $1 { typical motif. We don't allow our opponent to develop comfortably with e6-Nbd7. Black now has several moves. In this chapter, we'll cover } 6... Be4 { the second most played move, and the top choice of engines. Black hopes for Nxe4 Nxe4, followed by a check along the a5-e1 diagonal. } 7. Qb3 $1 { we bring out our queen in the typical fashion, looking to provoke a move with the black queen. } ( 7. Nxe4 Nxe4 $11 { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gd8a5,Ye7e6,Yf8b4] } ) 7... Qc7 { the best choice. } ( 7... Ra7 $6 { has been the most played move, but is inaccurate. We can now opt for } 8. Nxe4 { grabbing the active bishop. } 8... Nxe4 { [%cal Gd8a5] black's best bet. He wants to go for Qa5+ } ( 8... dxe4 $6 { runs into } 9. Nf5 $1 { [%cal Gf5g3,Gg3e2,Ye2c3] the knight will not get trapped. White has the pair of bishops and the weaknesses on e4 & b7 to attack. } 9... h5 ( 9... e6 10. Ng3 c5 11. Bd2 $16 h5 12. h4 Bd6 13. Rh3 $16 { [%cal Gd2c3,Ge1c1] } ) 10. Ng3 h4 11. Ne2 e6 12. Bd2 $14 { [%cal Ye2c3,Ye1c1] } ) 9. Nf3 { we solidly retreat. } 9... Qa5+ ( 9... e6 { is comfortably met with } 10. Nd2 $1 Nxd2 ( 10... Nf6 11. g3 Bd6 12. Bg2 $16 { [%csl Ra7,Gc4,Gd4,Ge4][%cal Ge3e4, Ge1g1] } ) 11. Bxd2 Be7 12. Bd3 $14 ) 10. Nd2 e6 11. Bd3 $16 { because of the inclusion of Qb3 Ra7, white has a much better game. The rook is misplaced. We would like to take on e4 next, followed by 0-0. } ) ( 7... b5 { is comfortably met with } 8. cxd5 Bxd5 ( 8... cxd5 { allows us to attack the 'hook' with } 9. a4 $16 { [%csl Rb5] } ) 9. Qc2 e6 10. Nhf3 $14 { [%csl Rb5,Rc6,Rd5][%cal Yf1e2,Gf1d3,Ye3e4, Ya2a4] white remains better due to the extra space in the centre. Our plans include a2-a4, Bd3/Be2, 0-0, e4. } ) 8. Nxe4 { the right time. Black has to spend an additional tempo playing Qc7-Qa5. } 8... dxe4 { stopping the h4-knight from returning to f3. This has been the preference of correspondence players. } ( 8... Nxe4 { runs into } 9. cxd5 { Black can try to recover the pawn and deliver a check with } 9... Qa5+ { but we are not afraid to move the king. After } 10. Ke2 cxd5 11. Qxb7 $16 { we keep decisive threats. Black is forced to enter the ending with Qb5, but we keep an extra pawn. } ) 9. f3 $1 { [%cal Yf3e4,Gh4f3] } 9... c5 $1 { striking the centre. } ( 9... exf3 10. gxf3 { [%cal Gf3f4] gives us a huge centre. } 10... Nbd7 11. f4 e6 12. Nf3 c5 13. Bg2 $14 ) 10. fxe4 Nxe4 11. g3 { [%cal Yf1g2] } 11... Nd6 $5 { pre-empting Bg2. } ( 11... cxd4 12. exd4 $16 { [%csl Gc1,Gc4,Gd4,Gf1] } ) 12. Bg2 Nd7 ( 12... cxd4 $6 13. exd4 $16 { [%csl Rb7,Gc1,Gc4,Gd4,Gg2] the c4-pawn is untouchable due to the hanging pawn on b7. } ) 13. Qc2 $1 { [%cal Gb2b3] and we can consolidate with b3, so we will have a stable strategic edge. } 13... cxd4 ( 13... e6 14. b3 $16 ) 14. exd4 Qxc4 15. Qxc4 Nxc4 16. Bxb7 Ra7 17. Bg2 $14 { We have a stable strategic edge thanks to the pair of bishops. White went on to win in } 17... g6 18. b3 Nd6 19. Be3 Bg7 20. Rc1 O-O 21. Nf3 $14 { [%cal Ge1e2] 1-0 (51) Rogachev,V (2144) -Susla,V (2357) LSS email 2017 } *
