1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Nbd2 Bf5 6. Nh4 { the starting point of this chapter. In this chapter, we will all of the black's options, except for Be4, which was covered in the previous chapter. } 6... Bg4 { the most played move. Black provokes us to play Qb3, so they can play b5. } ( 6... Be6 { [%cal Gg7g6,Yf8g7] is an interesting attempt, tried by GM Kobalia a few times. He wants to finish his development with g6-Bg7 next. } 7. h3 $1 { a very concrete prophylaxis against Bg4. We want to play b3 on the next move. } ( 7. b3 { would have been ideal, but black the very interesting } 7... Bg4 $5 { and the point is after } ( 7... g5 { is also a move to watch out for } ) 8. Qc2 e6 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Ne4 { [%cal Yc2b3] we don't have Qb3 anymore, unlike the main line. } ) 7... g6 ( 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bxc4 9. Nxc4 $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge3] we have a slightly better position thanks to the space advantage. } ) ( 7... b5 $6 8. c5 $16 { [%cal Gf1d3,Gf2f4] } ) 8. b3 Bg7 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Bd3 { [%cal Rf6e4,Gd3e4] } 10... O-O 11. O-O { If we can develop comfortably with Qc2, we should have a great position. Therefore, black must challenge our position with } 11... c5 { however, after } 12. Re1 $14 { [%csl Re6][%cal Gd2f3] White's position is clearly much more easier to handle. } 12... cxd4 ( 12... Rc8 13. Rc1 { [%cal Gh4f3] doesn't change much } ) 13. exd4 Nh5 ( 13... Nb8 { [%csl Rd4][%cal Yb8c6] computer's top choice. } 14. Ndf3 $1 Nc6 15. Ne5 dxc4 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. bxc4 $14 { [%csl Ra6,Gc4,Rc6,Gd4,Gf3][%cal Yh4f3] } ) 14. Bf1 $14 { [%csl Re6][%cal Yd2f3,Yf3g5,Yf3e5] } ) ( 6... e6 $6 7. Nxf5 $14 exf5 8. Qb3 { gives us a comfortable position without the slightest of problems. } 8... Qd7 ( 8... Ra7 9. a4 $1 a5 ( 9... Bd6 10. a5 Bc7 11. Qb4 $14 ) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Bb5+ $14 ) 9. Bd3 g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Nf3 $14 { [%cal Gc1d2,Ya2a4,Ya4a5] } ) ( 6... Bg6 $6 7. g4 $1 { [%cal Gg4g5,Yh4g6,Gh2h4] preparing g5-Ng6-h4. } 7... dxc4 ( 7... e6 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. g5 Nfd7 10. h4 Be7 11. Bg2 $16 ) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. Bxc4 e6 10. g5 Nd5 11. h4 $14 { we would like to finish our development next, by moving the knight, Bd2, moving the queen, and castling long, followed by opening up the kingside with h5. } ) 7. Qc2 e6 $6 { the most played move, but this allows to play } ( 7... g6 8. h3 Be6 9. b3 { gives us a favourable version of the 6...Be6 line. We have the line with an extra move, Qc2, which is beneficial for White. } 9... Bg7 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Be2 $14 { Is just very comfortable for white } ) ( 7... b5 8. b3 $16 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Yh2h3,Yh4f3,Yf3e5] } ) 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 $14 { with a sizeable advantage. Black's best bet is to play } 9... Ne4 $1 ( { the natural } 9... Bg6 $6 { runs into } 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. g5 Nfd7 ( 11... Nh5 12. h4 $16 ) 12. h4 { where white is much better thanks to the pair of bishops, space and better pawn structure. White managed to win comfortably in: 1-0 (30) Evtyukhin,S (2302) -Kaminski,J (1918) ICCF email 2018 } ) ( 9... g5 $5 10. gxh5 gxh4 11. Rg1 $1 { [%cal Gg1g8] grabbing the open file. } 11... Nxh5 12. Be2 Nf6 13. e4 $1 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] } 13... Bb4 ( 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 $16 { [%csl Re8][%cal Gc1g5,Yc1e3,Ye1c1] } ) 14. e5 Ne4 15. a3 Bxd2+ 16. Bxd2 Nxd2 17. Qxd2 $16 { [%cal Ge1c1,Ge2h5] } ) 10. Nxe4 Qxh4 ( 10... dxe4 11. Qb3 $1 b5 12. Ng2 $16 { [%cal Yh5g6,Rg2f4] } ) 11. cxd5 exd5 ( 11... Bxg4 $6 { the tempting option, but we have the spectacular } 12. hxg4 $3 Qxh1 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. Bd2 $1 { [%csl Rb7,Re6,Re8][%cal Ge1c1] intending to castle long. White has a safer king, pair of bishops in an open position, and weaknesses on b7 & e6 to attack. } 14... Qf3 { [%cal Yf3d1] trying to stop 0-0-0 } ( 14... Nd7 15. O-O-O $16 ) 15. Qb3 $1 Qxe4 ( 15... b5 16. Qxe6+ $18 ) 16. Qxb7 Qxg4 17. Bc4 $1 { bringing all pieces to the party } ( 17. Qxa8 Bd6 $11 { [%cal Ye8g8,Yg4g1] } ) 17... Be7 { and here white has the stunning } ( 17... Bd6 18. Qc8+ Ke7 19. Qxh8 $18 ) 18. f3 $3 { [%csl Re6] looking to deflect the queen away from the e6-pawn. } 18... Qg1+ ( 18... Qg3+ 19. Ke2 O-O 20. Qxe7 Qxf3+ 21. Kd3 $16 { [%csl Ra8,Re6][%cal Ge7b7] } ) ( 18... Bh4+ 19. Ke2 Qg2+ 20. Kd3 $16 ) 19. Ke2 Qxa1 $4 { this runs into } ( 19... Qg2+ 20. Kd3 $16 ) 20. Qc8+ Bd8 21. Qxe6+ Be7 22. Qf7+ Kd7 23. Be6+ Kd6 24. Bb4+ $18 { with a mate to follow soon. } ( 24. Bg4 $18 { mates } ) ) 12. Qb3 $1 { [%csl Rb7] Black has trouble defending the b7-weakness. } 12... Bg6 ( 12... b5 13. gxh5 Qxe4 14. Rg1 $16 { [%csl Rc6,Re8,Rf8][%cal Gf1d3,Gc1d2,Gb3c2] } ) ( 12... Qe7 13. gxh5 dxe4 14. Bd2 $18 { [%csl Re8][%cal Gh1g1] } ) 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. f4 f6 15. h4 $16 { [%csl Gd4,Ge3, Gf4,Gg4,Gh4][%cal Yh4h5,Yc1d2,Ye1c1] } *
