1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Nbd2 Bg4 { one of the most solid options out there for Black. } ( 5... b5 $6 { this is one of the most played moves, though it is quite weak. } 6. b3 $16 { With the knight on d2, Black's plans of b5 are ineffective. } 6... Bf5 ( 6... Bg4 $6 7. h3 Bxf3 ( 7... Bh5 $2 { this is met typically with } 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 $16 { [%cal Yh3h4,Yh4h5,Yg4g5] } ) 8. Nxf3 $16 { [%csl Gc1,Rc6,Gf1] we now have a stable advantage thanks to the weak black pawns and our advantage of the pair of bishops. } 8... e6 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. O-O Bd6 11. Qc2 O-O 12. Bb2 $16 { [%csl Ra6,Rb5,Rc6][%cal Gf3e5,Ra2a4] } ) 7. a4 { attacking the weaknesses. } 7... bxc4 ( 7... b4 8. Ne5 $16 { [%csl Rc6] } 8... e6 9. g4 $18 { [%cal Yh2h4] } ) 8. bxc4 e6 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ba3 $16 { [%csl Ra6, Rc6][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] } ) ( 5... g6 6. Bd3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. b4 $1 { [%csl Ra5, Rc5][%cal Ya2a4,Yb4b5,Yd2b3] we look to expand on the queenside. } 8... Bg4 $5 ( 8... a5 9. bxa5 Qxa5 10. a4 $14 { [%csl Re7][%cal Ya4a5,Gd1b3,Gc1a3,Yd2b3,Gf3e5] } ) 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. h3 $1 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 e6 12. a4 $14 { [%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc4,Gd4][%cal Gb4b5,Yc1a3] with a controlled advantage for white. We plan to open the queenside after finishing our development. The only to watch out for is the e5-break for Black. } ) 6. h3 { looking to win the bishop pair. } 6... Bxf3 ( 6... Bh5 $2 { runs into the thematic } 7. g4 $1 Bg6 8. Ne5 { [%cal Gh3h4] intending h4. After } 8... Nbd7 9. Nxg6 hxg6 10. g5 $1 Nh5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Qb3 e6 13. Nf3 $16 { [%csl Gb3,Rb7][%cal Yc1d2,Ya1c1,Ge1c1,Yf1d3,Ye1e2] White has a better position thanks to the pair of bishops, more active pieces and the batter pawn structure. We can play Bd2-0-0-0 next, or Bd2-Rc1-Bd3-Ke2. } ) 7. Nxf3 e6 8. Qb3 $1 { [%csl Gb4] stopping Bb4, and hitting the pawn on b7. We also keep an eye out for the e5-breaks. } ( 8. Bd3 $6 Nbd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. b3 Ne4 $11 ) 8... Qc7 9. Bd3 { developing the pieces normally } 9... Nbd7 10. O-O Bd6 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Rac1 Rfe8 13. a4 a5 14. Rfd1 $14 { [%cal Gd2e1,Yd3f1,Yg2g3,Yh3h4,Yf1h3,Yd1d2,Yd2c2] the position is quite solid but white clearly enjoys a small advantage. } *
