1. d4 { Welcome to the second segment of the course where we cover the Semi-Slav variation. This is considered to be more dynamic from Black's point of view. However, strategically speaking, white has a slightly better position typically when compared to the Slav systems. In this chapter, we will be covering 5...a6, one of the big old lines, along with some sidelines for black move 3 & 5. } 1... d5 ( { various move orders may take us to the desired position. } 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6 ) 2. c4 c6 ( 2... e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 c6 { Is the usual move order, if black players head for this system via the QGD variation. } ) 3. Nf3 Nf6 ( 3... e6 4. e3 { The Stonewall system. Black increases grip over the e4-square, but weakens e5. } 4... f5 5. Be2 Bd6 { this is the most common way of playing these positions. } ( 5... Nf6 6. O-O { the bishop is inferiorly placed on e7 in these structures. } 6... Be7 $6 ( 6... Nbd7 { allows us to exploit black's move order with } 7. Ng5 $1 Qe7 { [%csl Rf8] } 8. Nc3 $16 h6 $6 9. Bh5+ $18 ) ( 6... Bd6 { transposes } ) 7. b3 { [%cal Yc1b2,Yb1d2] } 7... O-O 8. Bb2 Nbd7 9. Ng5 { a typical motif, when the black bishop is on e7. Black finds it hard to defend e6. } 9... Nb8 { forced } 10. Nd2 Bd7 11. c5 $14 { [%cal Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Ya2a4] } ) 6. O-O Nf6 { and here I recommend going for } 7. c5 $5 { with the idea of launching a queenside assault after } 7... Bc7 8. b4 $1 O-O 9. a4 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Yb4b5,Yb5c6,Ya4a5] } 9... Nbd7 10. Bb2 { stopping e5. } ( 10. b5 e5 ) 10... Qe7 11. b5 { the right time to strike. } 11... e5 { we can now meet this with } 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 Bxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Qd4 $14 { with a very pleasant position for White. } ) 4. Nc3 ( { This is our usual response against the Slav. However, the Semi-Slav may come via various move orders, so the move orders are not a big concern. } 4. e3 ) 4... e6 5. e3 { The Meran system. Just like the Slav, we claim strategic superiority due to the extra space in the centre. In this chapter, we will be covering one of Black's most solid options a6, along with some other sidelines. } 5... a6 { [%cal Yb7b5,Yc6c5,Gd5c4][%emt 0: 00:17] intending dxc4, followed by b5-c5. } ( 5... Bd6 6. Qc2 O-O 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. O-O { transposes to the main line of the system,which is covered in further chapters. } ) ( 5... Be7 $5 { an interesting sideline. Black puts the bishop on an inferior square. However, the benefit is that white won't be able to play e3-e4 in some lines. } 6. Bd3 $5 { One of the very rare times we opt for Bd3 over Qc2. } ( 6. Qc2 O-O 7. Bd3 c5 $5 { was my reason to refrain from 6.Qc2. } ) 6... O-O { the main line. } ( 6... dxc4 { the recent fad. } 7. Bxc4 b5 ( 7... c5 { is slightly weaker. We keep a typical advantage with } 8. Qe2 $1 { [%cal Gd4c5] } 8... cxd4 9. exd4 O-O 10. O-O $14 { [%cal Gc1g5,Ga1d1] } ) 8. Bd3 $1 b4 ( 8... Bb7 $6 9. a3 $14 { [%cal Ya3b4] stopping b4. } 9... a6 ( 9... O-O 10. e4 $14 ) 10. Qc2 $1 { [%cal Yd4c5] } 10... Nbd7 11. b4 $14 ) 9. Na4 Nbd7 10. O-O Bb7 ( 10... c5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Nxc5 Bxc5 13. e4 $14 { [%cal Yc1f4,Ya1c1,Ye4e5] } ) 11. e4 { we gain space in the centre. } 11... Rc8 { [%cal Yc6c5] intending c5. } ( 11... c5 $6 12. e5 Nd5 13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. dxc5 { [%csl Re8][%cal Gd3b5] } 14... O-O 15. Qc2 $16 ) 12. a3 $5 { extremely rare. We concentrate our focus towards the c5-break. } 12... bxa3 ( 12... c5 $6 13. Nxc5 $1 Nxc5 ( 13... Bxc5 14. dxc5 $16 ) 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. axb4 $16 ) 13. b4 $1 { [%csl Gb4,Rc5,Gd4][%cal Yc6c5] the point. We look to create a grip over the c5-square. The critical response seems to be } 13... Bxb4 14. Bxa3 Bxa3 15. Rxa3 { [%csl Ra7,Rb7,Rc6,Gd4,Ge4] where white enjoys the grip over the centre and the Queenside. } 15... c5 $1 { trying to open files for the pieces. However, we have some tactical shots with the black king in centre. } ( 15... O-O 16. e5 $16 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Ga4c5] } ) 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Rxc5 18. Qb1 $1 Bc6 19. Rc1 Rxc1+ 20. Qxc1 Bd7 21. e5 ( 21. Rxa7 $5 ) 21... Nd5 22. Qg5 Qxg5 23. Nxg5 $5 { We keep good practical chances in the position. } ) ( 6... Nbd7 7. b3 O-O { tr. } ) 7. b3 { [%cal Yb3c4] reinforcing the support over the c5-square. } 7... Nbd7 8. Bb2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 { [%cal Yf3e5,Ge3e4] we have to plans in these positions. Either go for the e4-break, or prepare Ne5. } 10... h6 ( 10... Qc7 11. Ne5 $1 c5 12. f4 cxd4 13. exd4 dxc4 14. bxc4 $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gf4] } ) 11. Rfd1 Rc8 12. Qe2 { waiting for Qc7. } ( 12. Ne5 $5 ) 12... Qc7 13. Rac1 Rfe8 14. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Gf2f4] } ) ( 5... Nbd7 6. Qc2 Be7 7. b3 $14 ) ( 5... Bb4 $6 6. Qc2 O-O 7. Be2 { The combination of c6-Bb4 isn't great. } 7... Nbd7 8. O-O b6 9. cxd5 $1 cxd5 10. Bd2 Bb7 11. Qb3 { winning a free tempo. } 11... Be7 12. Rfc1 Qb8 13. Rc2 $14 ) ( 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 $16 { [%csl Rc6] } ) 6. b3 { [%cal Yb3c4] looking to recapture with the pawn to maintain the spacial advantage in the centre. } 6... Bb4 { the most ambitious response for Black. Other moves are weaker. } ( 6... b5 $6 7. c5 Nbd7 8. Bb2 $16 { [%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Gf1d3,Yc3e2,Ye2f4] } ) ( 6... c5 7. Bd3 { we continue developing normally without bothering about the central tension. } 7... Nc6 ( 7... cxd4 8. exd4 Bb4 ( 8... dxc4 9. bxc4 Bb4 10. Qb3 $16 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } ) 9. Bb2 b6 10. a3 $1 { initiating a sequence of forced moves with } 10... Bd6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qe2+ Qe7 14. Ne5 { white remains slightly better due to the activity of the pieces. } ) 8. O-O dxc4 9. bxc4 cxd4 10. exd4 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } 10... Nxd4 { the critical test. } 11. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 $5 ( 11... Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 $16 ) ( 11... Be7 $6 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Be3 Qe5 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Rb1 O-O 16. Qc2 $16 ) 12. Bxe4 Bc5 13. Bb2 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 O-O 15. Rad1 Qh4 16. Be5 $44 ) 7. Bd2 Nbd7 ( 7... O-O 8. Bd3 Nbd7 { transposes to the main line. } ) ( 7... Bd6 8. c5 $1 Bc7 9. Ne5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 9... Bxe5 ( 9... O-O 10. f4 $14 { [%cal Yf1d3,Ya1c1] } ) 10. dxe5 Nfd7 11. Na4 Nxe5 12. Nb6 Ra7 13. Bc3 $16 { we are a pawn down, but our activity compensates fully for the missing pawn. } ) 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O { the key branching point of this system. Black has two big choices. } 9... Bd6 ( 9... Qe7 { [%cal Ye6e5] the other main line. Black is intending to push e5 next. } 10. h3 { a very subtle move. White gets ready against the e5 break. } 10... e5 ( 10... h6 { returning the favour. Black is waiting too } 11. Bc2 $1 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1d5,Ye6e5] we continue the waiting game. The idea of Bc2 is to keep an indirect eye on the d5-pawn. } ( 11. Re1 e5 $11 ) 11... Rd8 { black is waiting too } ( 11... e5 { is met with the typical } 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 { and now } 14. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 $14 ) 12. Re1 e5 { finally! } 13. a3 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 e4 15. Nd2 Nf8 { it seems the Black has a decent position, but with Re1, it's now possible to play } 16. f3 $1 { [%cal Yf3e4] after } 16... Bf5 17. Bb4 Qe6 18. g4 Bh7 19. f4 { [%csl Gb3,Gc4,Gd4,Ge3,Gf4,Gg4,Rh7] we have a pleasant position in our hands. } ) 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Nxd5 { the typical tactical motif } 13... Nxd5 14. cxd5 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Qxd5 ( 15... cxd5 16. Rad1 $14 { [%csl Rd5] } ) 16. Qc2 $1 g6 17. f4 { the point. We increase the control over the centre. } 17... Re8 18. e4 Qd4+ 19. Kh2 $14 { [%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Ya1e1,Ga1d1,Ge4e5] } ) 10. Re1 { [%cal Ye3e4] this time, we eye for the e4 break. } 10... h6 $5 { black continues with the waiting strategy } ( 10... e5 { is met with } 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 $1 { [%csl Rc8] looking to exploit Black's lack of development. } 12... exd4 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nf6 15. h3 $1 { [%cal Yh3g4,Rc8g4] } 15... Nxd5 ( 15... h6 16. Qc1 $14 ) 16. Nxd4 $14 { White keeps a slight edge thanks to the active positioning of pieces. A critical line seems } 16... Nf4 17. Be4 Be5 $5 { but white can respond with } 18. Bxf4 Bxf4 19. Qf3 { keeping some advantage. Some sample lines- } 19... Qf6 ( 19... Bd2 20. Re2 Qxd4 21. Rd1 $14 ) ( 19... Qxd4 20. Qxf4 $16 ) 20. Rad1 ) ( 10... Re8 11. Qc2 h6 12. e4 { striking the centre at the right time. } 12... dxc4 $5 ( 12... dxe4 13. Nxe4 $16 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } ) 13. bxc4 e5 14. c5 $1 Bc7 15. Rad1 exd4 16. Ne2 $1 { [%csl Gc5,Gd1,Gd2,Gd3,Ge1, Ge2,Ge4,Gf3][%cal Ye2d4] We intend to recover the pawn, and thus keep an edge thanks to the active pieces and centre control. } 16... Qe7 ( 16... Ng4 17. Nexd4 $1 Nde5 { looks ambitious, but after } 18. Bf1 Qf6 19. h3 Nxf3+ 20. Nxf3 Ne5 21. Nd4 $14 { [%cal Yd4f5] we keep a comfortable advantage } ) 17. Rc1 $1 Rd8 ( 17... Ng4 18. Nexd4 Nde5 19. h3 $14 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. f4 Bc7 23. f5 $14 { [%csl Rc8] } ) 18. h3 $1 { [%csl Rc8] } 18... Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. f4 Bc7 21. Rf1 Be6 22. Be1 $16 { [%cal Ge1h4,Ge4e5] we keep great attacking chances. } ) 11. Rc1 $5 e5 { Black has to go for this, sooner or later } 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. h3 { [%cal Yh3g4] } 15... Bb8 { the most critical } ( 15... Re8 { is comfortably met with } 16. Ne2 { [%csl Rd5][%cal Gd2c3] intending Bc3 } 16... Bd6 ( 16... Bd7 17. Bc3 $14 ) 17. Bc3 Ne4 $5 18. Bxe4 $1 Rxe4 19. Rf1 { deep prophylaxis against Qg5. The idea is to meet } ( 19. Qd3 Qg5 $13 ) 19... Qg5 { with } 20. f4 $1 { [%csl Rg7][%cal Gf1f3,Gf3g3] intending to play Rf3 next. } 20... Qe7 21. Bd4 $14 ) 16. Ne2 Qd6 17. Nf4 $1 g5 $2 { looks tempting but spoils Black's king safety. We can comfortably play } ( 17... Re8 18. Bc3 $14 ) 18. Nh5 $16 { without worrying about } 18... Qh2+ { as we have } 19. Kf1 $16 Qh1+ $4 20. Ke2 $18 { Chapter 17: Semi-Slav 5...a6 [Admin] } *
