1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 b6 $5 { a modern way of playing. Black hasn't committed to the f8-bishop yet and looks to finish the queenside development with b6-Bb7. The drawback, though, is that we have chances to get the e4 break in a lot of variations. } 7. Bd3 Bb7 ( 7... Ba6 { is weaker. We can just play } 8. b3 Bb4 { was tried by Kramnik, but we keep a reasonably decent advantage with the simple } 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 { [%csl Gc1,Gd3] something like } 10... c5 { can be met with } 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 $14 { [%csl Rb6][%cal Ya4a5] } ) 8. O-O Be7 { this is supposed to be the critical system here. } ( 8... Bd6 $6 { allows to play } 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Qc7 { [%cal Yc6c5] Black's best bet. He is hoping for the c5-break. } ( 11... Nf6 { allows us to play the typical } 12. Bg5 $1 { intending to meet } 12... Be7 { with } 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. c5 $16 { [%csl Rb7] } ) 12. b4 $1 { the strongest response. } ( 12. Re1 $16 c5 $2 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. d5 $18 ) 12... Bxb4 13. c5 bxc5 14. a3 Ba5 15. dxc5 $16 { [%csl Ra5,Rb7] } ) ( 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 c5 { is possible, but after } 10. Rd1 { Black has nothing better than transposing with } 10... Be7 ( 10... cxd4 $2 11. exd4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 { is bad for black. After } 12... Bd6 13. d5 $1 e5 14. Bg5 O-O 15. Bb5 $16 { White had a great position, and went on to win comfortably in : 1-0 (42) Caruana,F (2847) -Yoo,C (2463) Almaty 2022 } ) ) 9. Rd1 { preparing against the c5 break in the best possible manner. } 9... Qc7 { the most played move in the position, but not the strongest. } ( 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 c5 { is the critical test. } 11. Ng5 { not the most popular, but quite testing. We pose immediate problems. } 11... cxd4 { the only way to remain in the game. } ( 11... h6 $4 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bxe6 $1 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gd4c5,Yc2g6] } 13... Nf8 $1 { the only defense. } 14. Qa4+ N6d7 15. Bb3 $16 { [%cal Ya4c4,Gc3d5] we are totally dominating the board. } ) ( 11... Qc7 { runs into the thematic } 12. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 13. Nxe6 Qc8 ( 13... Qc6 $4 14. d5 $18 { further worsens black's position. } ) 14. Nxg7+ $16 { [%csl Re8] We have 3 pawns+ a great initiative for the missing piece. } ) ( 11... Qc8 12. Qb3 $14 { [%cal Yc4e6] } ) 12. exd4 O-O 13. d5 { this already looks dangerous practically for Black. Black needs to know the accurate } 13... Qc8 $1 { to stay in the game. Not easy to evaluate this in a practical game. } ( 13... exd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Rc8 16. Qf5 $14 ) ( 13... Rc8 14. dxe6 $18 ) 14. d6 $5 { we are still continuing to pose problems. } 14... Qc6 { the only defense! } ( 14... Bxd6 15. Rxd6 Qxc4 16. Rxd7 $16 { [%csl Rh7] } ) ( 14... Qxc4 15. dxe7 Rfe8 16. Rxd7 $18 { [%csl Rh7] } ) 15. Nge4 Qxc4 ( 15... Nxe4 16. Bb5 $18 ) 16. dxe7 Rfe8 { again, the only move for Black. } ( 16... Rfb8 17. Nd6 Qc6 18. Nxb7 Rxb7 19. Qe2 $14 { [%cal Gc1g5,Ya1c1] } ) 17. Nd6 Qc6 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 19. Nb5 Rxe7 20. Bg5 { and we can stop the preparation part here. We keep good chances due to the activity of our pieces. Some sample lines- } 20... Rc8 ( 20... h6 21. Nd6 Qb8 22. Bh4 ) 21. Qa4 Qb8 $1 ( 21... Rc5 $6 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Nd6 Qa8 24. Qf4 $16 { [%csl Gd6,Rf6,Rg8][%cal Gh2h4,Yd1d3] } ) 22. Qxa7 Qxa7 23. Nxa7 $14 ) ( 9... O-O 10. b3 Rc8 11. Bb2 { [%cal Ge3e4,Yf3e5,Ra2a4,Ra4a5] These positions are almost every time pleasant for White. As discussed earlier, we either go for e4, or Ne5, or a4-a5. } 11... h6 ( 11... Qc7 12. a4 $1 a5 13. Rac1 Rfd8 14. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Gf2f4] clubbing both the important ideas! } ) 12. Qe2 { waiting for Qc7, as usual } 12... Qc7 13. Rac1 { [%csl Rc7][%cal Yf3e5,Yc4d5] } 13... Qb8 ( 13... dxc4 $6 14. bxc4 c5 15. Ne5 $1 cxd4 16. exd4 $14 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qc6 18. Qf1 $16 { [%csl Rd6][%cal Yd3e4,Gc3b5] } ) ( 13... Rfe8 14. Bb1 Qb8 15. Ne5 $16 ) 14. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Yf2f4,Yd3b1] we'll follow with f4 next, with good attacking chances. } ) 10. b3 O-O 11. a4 $14 { part of our typical ideas. We provoke a5, so that c5 break weakens the b5 square. } 11... c5 ( 11... Rac8 $6 12. a5 $14 bxa5 $2 13. c5 $16 { [%csl Ra5,Rb7] } ) ( 11... a5 12. Bb2 { [%csl Rb5][%cal Yc6c5,Gc3b5] } 12... Rac8 13. Rac1 { We are all set to play Ne5 next. } 13... Rfd8 ( 13... Bb4 14. Ne5 $14 ) 14. Ne5 $14 { [%cal Yc2e2,Yf2f4] } ) ( 11... Bb4 12. Bb2 Rac8 13. Ne5 $14 ) 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bb2 { [%csl Rb7,Rd5] these structures are very pleasant to play, as the b7-bishop is bad. } 13... Rac8 14. Rac1 g6 ( 14... c4 $6 15. bxc4 dxc4 16. Bf5 $18 { [%csl Gd4,Ge3][%cal Yf3e5,Ge3e4] } ) 15. Qb1 Rfd8 16. Ne2 { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gb1a1, Ra1h8] } 16... Qb8 17. h3 Ne4 18. Ba1 $14 { [%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Ge2f4,Gb1b2] our plans include putting pressure on the c5-d5-b6 pawns, and trying to exploit the weaknesses on g7/h8. } *
