1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 { the best response strategically. The bishop is on the most active square. } 7. Be2 { I prefer this over Bd3, as the bishop is better suited here for the 8...e5 line. } 7... O-O 8. O-O e5 ( 8... Re8 $5 { a flexible move, hinting towards e5. } 9. b3 { we continue developing normally } 9... b6 ( 9... Qe7 10. Bb2 dxc4 11. bxc4 e5 12. a4 $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4][%cal Ya4a5, Ya5a6,Yc3a4] we keep good chances thanks to the space on the queenside. } ) ( 9... dxc4 { is typically met with } 10. bxc4 e5 11. a4 $14 ) 10. a4 $1 { we typically meet with b6 with a4-a5. } 10... a5 11. Bd3 { placing the bishop on the active diagonal. the c5 break would be a lot less effective now. } 11... Bb7 12. Bb2 Qe7 { [%cal Ye6e5] } 13. Rae1 $5 { a very interesting idea. We prepare e4, and provoke Bb4. } 13... Bb4 $5 ( 13... c5 $6 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Nb5 $14 ) ( 13... Rad8 14. e4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Rxe4 $14 { [%csl Gc4,Gd4] } ) ( 13... e5 14. e4 $1 { the point of Rae1. } 14... dxc4 15. Bxc4 exd4 16. Nxd4 Qe5 17. Nf3 Qc5 ( 17... Qh5 $2 18. Rd1 $16 Bc7 19. h3 { [%cal Yc3e2,Rf3d4,Rf2f4] } ) 18. h3 Ne5 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Bc1 $14 { [%cal Yg1h1,Yf2f4,Gc1e3] } ) 14. Re2 { [%cal Gf3e5] stepping outside of the pin. We are hinting towards Ne5. } 14... c5 15. Ne5 $5 { [%cal Gf2f4] the point of the sequence. } 15... cxd4 16. exd4 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nh5 18. g3 $1 g6 19. Nb5 { [%csl Rb6,Rd6][%cal Gb5d6,Gb2d4]  preparing Nd6. Bxd6 seems very risky due to the weaknesses on f6/g7. White has good chances in a practical game. } ) ( 8... b6 { one of the most critical sidelines in this chapter. Black wants to go for the typical Bb7-c5 positions. } 9. a4 a5 ( 9... Bb7 10. a5 $14 ) 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bb7 13. Rd1 { we are doing all we can to avoid c5. } 13... Qe7 ( 13... Qc7 $6 { allows to weaken black's kingside with } 14. Bd3 g6 15. Qh4 Rfe8 16. Bf1 $14 ) 14. Bf4 Nf6 { the critical test. } ( 14... Rfd8 { runs into } 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Ne5 { where we maintain the typical advantage. After } 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Qe7 18. Bf3 { stopping c5. } 18... Rab8 19. Qf4 c5 20. Bxb7 Rxb7 21. Rd6 { we have a very promising position thanks to the active rook. It's very hard for Black to defend these endgames practically. } ) 15. Bxd6 { as strong novelty } 15... Qxd6 16. Qe5 $1 Qb4 ( 16... Qe7 17. Ra3 $14 { [%csl Rb6][%cal Ga3b3] } ) 17. Ne1 $3 { the whole point. We want to kick the queen away with Nd3. The natural } 17... c5 { runs into } ( 17... Qxb2 18. Nd3 $16 { [%csl Rb2] } ) ( 17... Rad8 18. Nc2 $14 ) 18. Nc2 $1 Qxb2 19. Bd3 Rad8 20. Rdb1 Qc3 21. Qe2 { [%cal Ga1a3] where the Queen is trapped! } ) ( 8... a6 { allows us to grab space in the centre with } 9. e4 $16 ) ( 8... dxc4 { is covered in the next two chapters. } ) 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nb5 Bb8 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Bd2 $14 { [%cal Gd2c3] Seems like we can put some pressure here. We want to play Bc3 next. } 12... Bg4 { stopping Bc3. } ( 12... Ne4 13. Bc3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Ng5 15. Be2 a6 16. Nd4 $14 ) 13. Nbd4 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Qd6 15. g3 Bxf3 16. Nxf3 Ne4 17. Rad1 $14 { these positions are always much easier to play as white, as black has an isolated pawn and does not keep any attacking prospects. } *
