1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 { the starting point of this chapter. } 9. Bxc4 { We will be covering all of black's options apart from the main move 9...b5 in this chapter. } 9... a6 $5 { [%cal Yb7b5,Yc6c5] intending to play b5, followed by c5. } ( 9... e5 { is another popular move. Black wants to play exd4 followed by Nb6-Bg4 next, so the most testing option here is } 10. h3 $1 { [%cal Yh3g4,Rd7b6,Rc8g4] } 10... Qe7 ( 10... exd4 11. exd4 { [%csl Rc8][%cal Gc1g5] gives white a simple positional advantage. } 11... Nb6 12. Bb3 Nbd5 ( 12... Re8 13. Bg5 { [%cal Yf1e1,Ya1d1,Yf3e5] } ) ( 12... h6 $6 13. Bxh6 $16 { [%cal Yc2g6] } ) 13. Bg5 $14 ) ( 10... h6 11. Rd1 { [%cal Yd4e5] } 11... exd4 ( 11... Qe7 12. Nh4 $14 { [%cal Yh4f5] } ) 12. Nxd4 Nb6 13. Bf1 Qe7 14. e4 $14 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Yc1e3] we remain due to the extra space and mobility in the centre. } ) 11. a3 { [%cal Yc4a2] We are waiting for black to take on d4 to recapture with the e-pawn, opening up the c1-h6 diagonal. } 11... Bb8 { the main move. We meet this by playing } ( 11... e4 12. Ng5 Nb6 13. Ba2 Bf5 14. f3 $14 ) ( 11... Bc7 12. Ba2 h6 13. Nh4 $14 { [%cal Gh4f5] } ) 12. Ba2 { [%cal Gb2b4] getting ready to play dxe5 at the right time. } 12... h6 13. dxe5 { finally! } 13... Nxe5 14. Nd4 $1 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 14... c5 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 $14 { [%csl Ga2][%cal Yf2f4] } ) ( 9... Qe7 10. h3 e5 11. a3 { transposes } ) ( 9... Qc7 10. Bd2 $1 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4 Bd6 14. Kh1 $14 { [%cal Ge3e4] } ) ( 9... b5 { is covered in the next chapter. } ) 10. Ng5 $5 { a rare, but extremely tricky move. We are being prophylactic against b5. } 10... Qc7 { the most played move. } ( 10... b5 11. Be2 { transposes to the next chapter. } ) ( 10... h6 11. Nge4 { the point of the operation. We look to establish control over the c5-square. } 11... Nxe4 ( 11... Bc7 12. b3 $14 { [%cal Gc1a3] } ) 12. Nxe4 Be7 13. Rd1 Qc7 14. b3 $1 e5 ( 14... c5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb2 { [%csl Ra8,Rc8] black has issues with development of the c8 bishop. } 16... b5 ( 16... Bd7 17. Qc3 $18 ) 17. Bd3 $18 { [%cal Gc2c7] } ) 15. Bb2 exd4 16. Bxd4 $16 { [%csl Gc4,Rc8,Gd4,Ge4] } ) ( 10... c5 11. Nce4 $1 { the best practical try } 11... Nxe4 ( 11... Bb8 $1 { this unplayed move (in OTB games) is black's best response. } 12. dxc5 Nxe4 $1 ( 12... Qc7 $6 { doesn't haunt us. After } 13. f4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxc5 15. Ng5 g6 16. a4 $14 { [%cal Ya4b5,Yb2b3,Yc1b2] we keep a stable edge thanks to the extra space. } ) 13. Nxe4 Nxc5 { the tactical point. } 14. Nxc5 Qc7 15. g3 Qxc5 { It seems like black is out of problems, but } 16. b4 $5 { still poses some practical problems. } 16... Qxb4 ( 16... Qc6 17. Bb2 b5 18. Qc3 ) 17. Rd1 Qe7 18. Bb2 { We keep some initiative. Some sample lines- } 18... Bd6 19. a4 e5 20. Qd3 Bc5 21. Qe4 $44 ) 12. Nxe4 Bb8 ( 12... Qc7 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. Rd1 $14 ) 13. a4 $14 { [%cal Ga1a3] a deep and testing novelty. We stop b5, and prepare the rook lift with Ra3. } 13... cxd4 14. exd4 Nb6 ( 14... h6 15. Ra3 $36 { [%cal Ga3h3] is what we were hoping for } ) 15. Ng5 g6 16. Bb3 $36 ) 11. e4 $1 { this pawn sac is the main idea behind the operation. We gain initiative. } 11... Bxh2+ ( 11... h6 12. e5 hxg5 13. exd6 Qxd6 14. Bxg5 { gives us excellent practical chances. Black has issues with development. } 14... c5 $1 { comp's top choice. } ( 14... Qxd4 15. Bb3 $14 { [%csl Rc8] } ) 15. Rad1 $5 { bringing all pieces into the game. } 15... Ng4 16. g3 cxd4 17. Ne4 Qc6 18. Rxd4 $5 ) 12. Kh1 { [%csl Rh2][%cal Ge4e5] } 12... c5 { played in the only recorded (correspondence) game. } ( 12... h6 13. Nf3 Bf4 14. e5 Bxc1 15. Raxc1 Nd5 16. Bb3 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 $14 { [%csl Rc8,Gd4,Ge5][%cal Yb3c2] we have a space advantage and keep chances to attack the kingside. Black has issues developing the c8 bishop. } ) ( 12... Bf4 $2 13. e5 $16 ) 13. e5 { we continue with our threats. } 13... h6 $1 ( 13... cxd4 14. exf6 $18 { [%csl Rh7][%cal Gc2h7] } ) 14. Nf3 Ng4 $1 { only this accurate move holds for Black. } ( 14... cxd4 15. exf6 Qxc4 16. fxg7 Re8 17. Kxh2 dxc3 18. Rh1 $14 { [%csl Rh6][%cal Yh2g1] } ) 15. Qe4 { deviating from the aforementioned game. } 15... cxd4 16. Qxg4 { Black is walking on a tight rope here. The only way black remains in the game is by playing } 16... Bxe5 $1 ( 16... Nxe5 17. Qxd4 $1 Nxf3 18. gxf3 $18 ) 17. Ne4 { and now the practically impossible } 17... h5 ( 17... Qxc4 18. Bxh6 $18 ) 18. Qxh5 Qxc4 19. Re1 Bf6 20. Bf4 $40 { White has a tremendous initiative. For example the natural } 20... Qd5 { loses to } 21. Be5 $18 *
