1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 { the point of deviation from the previous chapter. } 10. Be2 Bb7 { the main move by far. } ( { that being said, there's a couple of other moves which we should check. } 10... Qe7 { [%cal Ye6e5] intending e5. We continue by gaining space with } 11. e4 e5 { [%cal Rb5b4] } 12. a3 $1 { stopping b4. We are waiting for Bb7. } 12... a6 ( 12... Bb7 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nd4 $16 { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gd4f5] the point. } ) ( 12... exd4 13. Nxd4 $16 { [%csl Rc6,Gd4,Ge4][%cal Yd4f5, Yf2f4] } ) 13. Bg5 $1 { bringing the last minor piece into the game. } 13... h6 ( 13... Re8 14. Rad1 $14 ) 14. Bh4 Re8 15. Rad1 $14 { [%cal Yf1e1] we will follow up with Rfe1 next, followed by dxe5 and Nd4, if black goes for Bb7. } ) ( 10... a6 { the other critical sideline. We have a similiar approach to the a6 variation covered in the previous chapter. } 11. Ng5 $5 { [%cal Ye3e4,Yc3e4] intending Nce4/e4. } 11... Qc7 ( 11... h6 { allows to play } 12. Nge4 Be7 13. a3 $1 { [%csl Rc5][%cal Yb2b4]  with the threat of b4. } 13... a5 ( 13... Bb7 14. b4 a5 15. Rb1 $14 { [%csl Gb4,Rb7,Rc5,Rc6,Gd4,Ge4] with total domination over the c5-square. } ) ( 13... c5 $6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Nxb5 $16 ) 14. Nxf6+ $1 Nxf6 15. Rd1 { [%cal Ge3e4] } 15... Qb6 16. e4 e5 17. Be3 $14 { [%csl Rc6][%cal Gd4d5] } ) 12. e4 $1 { as we have seen in the previous chapter, we are sacrificing a pawn for initiative. } 12... Bxh2+ ( 12... h6 13. e5 hxg5 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Bxg5 { gives us the typical initiative. } 15... Qxd4 16. Rfe1 $1 Qc5 17. Qd2 $36 ) ( 12... e5 $6 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. f4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 $14 { [%csl Ge4,Gf4][%cal Ye4e5] } ) 13. Kh1 { [%cal Ge4e5] } 13... c5 $1 { Black has no other choice but to enter the complications. Other moves are significantly weaker. } ( 13... h6 $6 14. Nf3 Bf4 15. e5 Bxc1 16. Raxc1 Ne8 17. Ne4 $14 { [%csl Rc5,Rc6,Gd4,Ge4,Ge5,Gf3][%cal Yf3d2,Yd2b3] Black's pieces lack oxygen. } ) ( 13... b4 $6 14. Na4 Bf4 15. e5 Bxg5 16. Bxg5 $14 { [%csl Rc5,Rc6] } ) ( 13... Bf4 $2 14. e5 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 $18 ) 14. e5 cxd4 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. f4 $1 { [%csl Rh2][%cal Yh1h2] looking to trap the bishop } 16... Bg3 ( 16... h6 17. Nge4 $16 { [%csl Rh2] } ) 17. Rf3 $1 h6 ( 17... Bh4 $6 18. Rh3 $1 dxc3 ( 18... Bxg5 19. fxg5 $18 ) 19. Rxh4 h6 20. Ne4 Nxe4 21. Qxe4 Bb7 22. Qe3 $16 ) 18. Rxg3 hxg5 { it seems that black is out of trouble, but after } 19. Rh3 $1 { we retain great attacking prospects. } 19... dxc3 ( 19... gxf4 20. Nd5 $4 { [%csl Rg8][%cal Gd5e7] } ) ( 19... g4 20. Nd5 { is similar } ) 20. Rxc3 $1 Qb6 21. fxg5 Nd5 22. Rh3 g6 23. Bf3 Qd4 24. Qd2 Qxd2 25. Bxd2 $14 { [%cal Yh1h2,Yh2g3,Ga1e1,Ge1e4, Ge4h4] } ) 11. e4 e5 { since the black bishop is on b7, it makes a lot of sense to play } 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nd4 { [%cal Gd4f5,Gf2f4] threatening f4/Nf5. } 13... Neg4 { the sharpest, and the principled response. } ( { other moves are weaker. } 13... b4 14. Nf5 $1 { [%csl Rd6] initiative! } 14... bxc3 15. Rd1 $1 { [%csl Rd6] } 15... Ne8 16. Qxc3 { [%csl Re5][%cal Gf5d6,Rc3e5] } 16... Qf6 17. f4 $1 { Black is bombarded with threats. The best response is to play } 17... Bc7 { but white remains better after the arising simplifications with } 18. fxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxe5 Bxe5 20. Be3 $14 { [%csl Ra7,Rb7, Rc6,Ge2,Ge3,Gf5][%cal Ye3c5] } ) ( 13... Re8 14. Nf5 Bf8 ( 14... Bc8 15. Nxd6 $16 ) 15. Bg5 { [%cal Gf2f4] this looks extremely scary for black. } 15... b4 16. f4 $1 Ned7 $1 ( 16... bxc3 $4 17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Nh6+ $18 { [%csl Rf6][%cal Yh6f7] } ) 17. Na4 Qa5 18. e5 Nd5 19. Rf3 { [%cal Gf5g7] We can stop memorization here, especially since } 19... N7b6 { runs into } 20. Nxg7 Qxa4 21. Qb1 Bxg7 22. Rh3 h5 23. Rxh5 $14 { with a huge attack on the kingside. } ) ( 13... Ng6 14. Nf5 $16 ) 14. Nf5 $5 { [%csl Rd6,Rg4][%cal Gf1d1,Yh2h3,Yf2f4] a very rare, and incredibly testing move. As I mentioned in the introduction, I came to know about this after one of my friends got butchered within a few moves. Strategically speaking, black is in huge trouble if we can roll those pawns. } 14... Bxh2+ ( 14... b4 $4 { was tried in few games, but after } 15. h3 bxc3 16. hxg4 $18 { white keeps a decisive advantage in: 1-0 (46) Koneru,H (2574) -Sargsyan,A (2382) Moscow 2019 } ) 15. Kh1 Bb8 { [%cal Gd8c7] it seems like the idea is to play Qc7 next, but the real idea is to just get the bishop out of the attack. } ( 15... g6 { is met with } 16. f3 gxf5 17. fxg4 $1 { with complications favouring White. } 17... Be5 ( 17... Nxg4 { the other critical try } 18. Rxf5 { [%cal Gf5g5,Ye2g4] } 18... Bf4 $1 { [%cal Rd8h4] threatening Qh4. We are forced to stop it with } 19. Rh5 Nf2+ 20. Kg1 Qd4 21. Kf1 $1 Bxc1 22. Qxc1 $14 { the position is still super complex, but white is still objectively better thanks to the attacking chances on the kingside. } ) 18. Rxf5 Qe7 19. Bf4 $1 { eliminating the important dark-squared bishop. } 19... Bxf4 20. Rxf4 Nd7 { [%cal Gd7e5] black now wants to play Ne5, and so we play } ( 20... Rad8 $5 21. Raf1 Nd7 { [%cal Yd7e5] } 22. e5 $1 { is similiar to the 20...Nd7 line } ) 21. e5 $1 { [%cal Gc3e4] sacrificing a pawn to activate our knight. After } 21... Nxe5 22. Ne4 f6 23. Raf1 $36 { we still retain the initiative. } ) ( 15... Bc8 { doesn't work now, as after } 16. g3 $16 { [%csl Rh2] the bishop is trapped } ) ( 15... Bc7 $4 16. Bg5 $18 { is already decisive. } 16... Qe8 { [%cal Ge8e5] } 17. f3 Qe5 18. g3 $1 Nh5 19. Rg1 $18 Ngf6 20. f4 { [%cal Ge4e5] the pawns are rolling up the board! } ) ( 15... b4 { this is the other reasonable option for black. However, after } 16. Bg5 bxc3 17. Bxg4 Be5 18. bxc3 Qa5 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. f4 $1 Qxc3 21. Qa4 $14 { [%csl Rb7,Rc6,Ge4,Gf4,Gf5,Gg4] } ) 16. Bg5 { and black needs to find } 16... Bc8 { the only move to remain in the game } ( 16... Qc7 $4 17. f4 $18 { [%cal Gg5f6, Ye4e5] is already decisive. } ) 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Nd6 { You could stop checking here, but for the sake of completeness, I would like to show a few more variations. } 18... Be6 { the only move to remain in the game. } ( 18... h6 19. Bh4 Be6 20. e5 $14 { an important positional motif in these positions. } 20... Nd5 ( 20... Nxe5 $4 21. Bxf6 $18 ) 21. Bg3 $1 { [%cal Gg3e5,Yc3e4] } ( 21. Nce4 Nxe5 $19 ) 21... Qe7 22. Nce4 $14 ) ( 18... b4 $4 19. e5 $18 Nxe5 ( 19... bxc3 $4 20. exf6 gxf6 21. Bxg4 Bxg4 22. Bxf6 $18 ) 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Nce4 $18 ) ( 18... a6 $4 19. e5 Nxe5 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. f4 $18 ) 19. e5 $5 { the best practical try. We add fuel to the fire. } 19... Nxe5 ( 19... Nd5 20. Bxg4 Bxg4 21. Rd4 Qd7 22. Nxd5 cxd5 23. Qd2 { [%cal Gg5f6] with good practical chances. A very important threat to know is Bf6. } ( 23. Rxd5 f6 $1 ) 23... h6 ( 23... Be6 24. Bf6 $40 ) ( 23... Qe6 24. Rxd5 h6 25. Bh4 $5 ) ( 23... Bxd6 24. exd6 f6 25. Bf4 $14 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Yf1c1,Yc1c7] } ) 24. Bxh6 gxh6 25. Qxh6 { Black holds, but with computerised play. The only way to equalise here is } 25... f5 26. f3 Bxd6 27. exd6 Rf7 $11 { which is just practically impossible. } 28. Kg1 Rh7 29. Qg5+ Rg7 30. Qh4 Rh7 31. Qg3 Qg7 $3 32. Rxd5 { the line still goes on, but Black should be fine. } ) 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. f4 { and it seems like the attack is very dangerous, but the very concrete and anti-positional } 21... Ng6 $3 { [%cal Gc7e7] let's black survive. That being said, even elite players aren't likely to find this OTB. } ( 21... Ng4 $4 22. Qe4 $18 { [%cal Ge2g4,Yd6e8,Rf4f5] gives us a decisive advantage. } ) 22. Nce4 ( 22. f5 Qe7 $3 { was the point behind Ng6. } 23. fxe6 Bxd6 24. exf7+ Kh8 ) 22... Qe7 { somehow, Black is surviving with the barest of margins. } 23. Qc3 $11 { we still keep some chances, but Black is very safe here. This sequence of moves from Black isn't easy, and the chances of your opponent making errors here are quite high! } ( { the natural } 23. f5 { runs into } 23... Bd5 $3 24. fxg6 fxg6 $17 { another impossible line to find OTB. } ) *
